title: Add access control over metrics
body:
In our use case, some metrics are sensitive (e.g. revenue). So we want to restrict some metrics to only a few roles.
In this pull request, I made the following changes: 
When editing the metrics, there is a new check box "Is restricted". If the check box is checked, only certain roles are allowed to use this metric. To grant the access to a role, give permissions like "metric access on [cluster1].[datasource1].[metric1](id:1)" to the role.
Any users without the permission will see the error message "Access to the metrics denied: metric1 (Status: 500)". It also happens when the user wants to access a post-aggregation metric that is dependent on metric1.
Currently only the access control over pure metrics (not post-aggregation metrics) is implemented.

title: Popover to generate iframe html tag when standalone button is clicked
body:
The embed button in slice view page will redirect the window to the standalone version of the slice. We made a small change on this and now it will pop a popover for instead. The popover will let user input the width and height they want for the iframe and the iframe tag can be copied from the popover.

Basically the source link of the iframe is just the standalone link of the slice and unauthorized users will not be able to access. We think that maintaining the view permission is a better way to do that, so the iframe tag is internal and not public.

The screenshots below will do a mini-demo.

title: Fix #529 1 "This Session's transaction has been rolled back"
body:
Fix one of the issues found in #529 

Background:
- When an object is modified by SQLAlchemy, it is invalidated so need to be fetched again from the DB
- If there's an exception during a transaction, SQLAlchemy performs a rollback and mark the connection as dirty.

Bug:
- When handling exceptions, the exception handler tries to access the name of the cluster in the main object. Since the name has been invalidated due to a write, SQLAlchemy tries to fetch it on a 'dirty' connection and spits out an error.
  Solution:
- Fetch the information for handling the exception before starting the process.

title: Druid Intervals Issues prevents metadata pull
body:
## Why is the change required ?

Caravel is not refreshing metadata with latest Druid Version.  Because of bug in 0.8 (which is fixed 0.8.2)  this was put in deliberately. Since this is open source project and its more likely that new folks would try with latest druid (which 0.9) this will become default issue. Fix is by introspecting druid version using /status API and setting intervals accordingly. 
## How is it tested ?

Manually patched the code tested with local installation (mac + druid 0.9) and default druid [wikiticker example](http://druid.io/docs/0.9.0/tutorials/quickstart.html). This was not working before the patch. 

Screenshots: 
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/391567/15597745/0d380dce-2388-11e6-9160-b267fa4d0844.png)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/391567/15597757/18b037c6-2388-11e6-8e2e-d7d6984d351b.png)
## Any dependencies for merging this ?

None
## References:

https://github.com/airbnb/caravel/issues/445

title: Reactify dashboard grid
body:
Using [react-grid-layout](https://github.com/STRML/react-grid-layout).
##### Notable changes:
- Resizing and dragging are smoother
- the grid is now responsive, the number of columns as well as column width will change based on browser width

---
##### Considerations:
- this may break some custom CSS. The most notable change is that slices are now `divs` instead of `lis`. The `gridster` class is still in place for legacy purposes.
- layouts that use less than 12 columns will not be centered anymore. We recommend always using 12 columns.
- you cannot increase the number of rows of a slice past the screen/browser bounds
- responsiveness isn't perfect yet, the number of columns at each breakpoint is fixed and can be made better. Also, you have to do a dashboard refresh to resize your slices after changing window size

This simplifies configuration of dashboards visible to anonymous users, while explicit grant of 'datasource_access' is still required.

title: Cosmetric tweaks in the CRUD list view
body:
@williaster @georgeke 
This was bugging me as sometimes the date would wrap in the middle in the list view. For the record the @renders decorator is provided by FAB (flask appbuilder) and allows to define a property for rendering a field. It's better than `@property` (which also works), because the sort options in the list views work and are bound to the field defined in `@renders`

title: Order by clause with Hive causes performance degradation.
body: Order by clause with Hive causes performance degradation. It doesn't really do anything else except on some cases causes queries to fail. I'm not sure if this is the right way to fix it, but on the other hand disabling order by really helps with performance. Otherwise, perhaps it would be wise to add an order by button to the web interface. So that the user could control it.

title: add unicode data to tests
body:
As promised, this PR:
- adds a csv with unicode data for testing to `caravel/data`
- adds a loading function for the data, activated with command line flag `--test` (and by the tests)
- adds a table, slice (pic below), and dashboard featuring unicode data (if `--test` is specified)

Note I changed the `sample` flag in the data load command in `bin/caravel`, as it didn't seem to be doing anything.

Also fixes #395.
